column37: In this scenario, trustworthy feels higher due to the presence of appeal, oversight by user council, transparency note, and the fact that system was designed in collaboration with students and teachers. Yet, I am still unaware how the process of the appeal works. In addition, I am still not sure whether all similar cases are treated in the similar way or not. However, I believe that the last stated doubt can be easily checked after practical usage of the system, I mean when there are similar cases and the system will act accordingly. Until it happens, I doubt I can be persuaded to believe or disbelieve in any outcomes regarding its possible decisions.

column20:
This system would feel more fair and trustworthy if it showed that it treats every patient and case with consistency, transparency, and respect for human values.

Specifically:

Fairness — If the AI makes decisions without bias toward age, gender, race, or social background.

Transparency — If it clearly explains how it reaches its conclusions, rather than giving “black box” answers.

Accountability — If there’s a clear way to review, question, or appeal the AI’s decisions.

Collaboration with humans — When it supports doctors instead of replacing them, showing that people still have final control.

Accuracy and reliability — Consistently giving correct and evidence-based results builds confidence.

If those qualities are missing — for example, if the system hides how it works, makes errors without explanation, or treats some patients unfairly — then it feels less trustworthy and less fair.
column21:
The feature that most improves accountability is transparent decision tracking — meaning the AI clearly records and explains every step of how it reached a decision.

This includes:

Explainable reasoning — showing the data, logic, and model outputs behind each recommendation.

Audit trails — keeping logs that allow experts to review and verify past decisions.

Human review options — allowing doctors or patients to challenge or override the AI’s conclusions.

Performance reporting — regularly publishing accuracy rates, error statistics, and updates.

In short: accountability grows when every decision can be traced, questioned, and verified by humans.
